segments.text: include all of the key core staff?
Well, core block, they go out and then they have elections to see who and their friends vote.
to see who gets an interview.
The people in their class vote, and the top three vote getters go to an interview process.
And inside the interview process, then they interview with people such as core staff, stuff like that.
So in the interview process, there are
the key people within the Corps Commander, Deputy Corps Commander, someone's from Parcel Mountain Cavalry, someone's from Ross Volunteers, stuff like that.
So I'm in the band.
Did it cost in that campaign for your senior yell leader, did that cost some money?
It cost money both years.
Where'd you raise the money?
Credit cards and my parents.
So you didn't raise money from other people?
No, I did not.
What would be the guesstimate of what?
A lot.
More.
My junior year, probably five.
Really?
Yeah, but that's taking into account everything.
That's taking into account cell phone bills, gas, I mean food for the people who helped out, the gifts that I got them when it was all done for helping out, stuff like that.
It was less my senior year just because I didn't have to work as hard my senior year.
I already had name recognition.
I already had all that kind of stuff.
In the campaign, the two years, is there anything you did that if you were doing it now you wouldn't do?
Anything that you realize was an error in judgment or ethics?
No, there really is not.
Maybe something I'd do different is when I'd go speak, I would say a lot more than what I did, especially my senior year.
Sometimes I wanted to play PC too much.
Does that make sense?
I didn't want to offend anyone, so I'd keep some of the stuff that I wanted to say just to myself just because that's fine.
Looking back on it, I kind of wish I would have said some stuff that would have maybe alleviated some problems that we've had.
Did you keep the bright, the special green color?
No, actually we didn't.
We changed it and the campaign kind of took on a different, kind of different feel to it that year.
Completely new people helped out.
It was a new group of people.
And that year was all about, it was so funny, it's almost like we started an organization.
And we called it Random Steps.
Because everyone that helped out was all about people opening up amongst themselves, not trying to become new people.
Does that make sense?
Like take steps personally.
And so, I mean, everything from taking random trips to Austin on a Tuesday night when we shouldn't have.

um to just anything and so what we ended up doing was uh that kind of became what it was and it became like best friends like they're probably two marriages are coming out of it out of the people and they didn't know each other before the before the campaign started and now two people will probably end up getting married um out of that best friendships roommates
A bunch of stuff.
So you had no opponent?
Well, we had opponents, but not from the Corps.
Not from the Corps cadets.
And your margin of victory was?
Bubba and I, the guy that I reigned with, we set records for the most votes that anyone has ever gotten at A&M.
Was he a civilian or a Corps?
No, he was Corps.
He got 40 more votes than I did, and...
We, he got 8,000 and I got right under 8,000.
And that is, we beat, the next closest person got 2,000.
So the margin of victory was substantial.
And of the five elected, were you the only civilian?
Once again, I was the only civilian.
And then you go before the?
Go before the board and interview.
And that board was there much difference in the background of the interview board in terms of core civilian or whatever?
It was all over.
I mean it was appointed by the student body president and so there were people from all over.
A true variety.
It was a true variety.
It sure was.
Did anybody either during the campaign or during the interview process come to you and try to get you to promise to do this, that or the other?
Not really.
Honestly, I mean, just because if you look at what yell leaders do, there's not a lot that we could promise.
They could be like, promise to do more yells, and we'll be like, okay, we'll do more yells.
You know, I mean, there's not, there's really nothing, not really.
Nobody asks you to come to the fraternity and sorority houses more or do this and Duncan more or anything.
No.
And...
then how did you learn you had been selected as the head yell leader?
We go through the interview process, and the three senior yell leaders who got interviewed, we would go up to Dr. Sutherland's office, and Dr. Sutherland would tell us who got it.
All three at the same time?
All three at the same time, and Rusty Thompson, who was our advisor, all four of us would be up there, and then Dr. Sutherland would tell us.
And it was weird, just because I never, I mean, no civilian has ever been a head yell leader before.
When you went in to that meeting,
You knew that the announcement was going to occur then?
Yeah.
What were your thoughts?
My thoughts were, don't worry about it.
It's not a big deal.
You're going to have fun next year.
Think about all the extra time you're going to have.
Just because a junior yell leader is much more time consuming than just a regular senior yell leader.
A head yell leader's time is much more, a lot more time consuming than just a junior yell leader.
But, so I was just like, man, I was trying to be positive.
I was just like, just because I knew, I was like there's no way that they're going to give a non-reg head yell leader.
It's just not going to happen.
Did he say anything unusual in making the announcement?
When he first started, about five minutes into his talk, I was like, I think I started Yell Leader.
Just because what he was talking on.

He was talking on changes within the Yell Leader organization and how they dealt with that and how when changes happened that it turned out to be some of the strongest years of Yell Leaders when the changes happened.
So when that happened, when he said that, I was just like, wow, something happened.
All right, so the announcement is made, and then did anyone then pull you aside in any manner and give you advice, guidance, counsel?
Not really, to be honest with you.
I think they were very upset that I won, they being the core yell leaders.
They were upset that I won.
Were they outwardly pleasant?
No, not at first, not the first week, not the first two weeks.
They weren't at all.
Last year's head yell leader didn't talk to me for about two weeks, wouldn't return my phone calls.
Really?
And then when we actually sat down and talked, he was very visibly upset and even angry at times.
for weird reasons, and it worked out fine.
I mean, everything, in the end, everything's fine.
But I remember being upset about that.
I mean, I was hurt by that.
But.
All right, then, as you go back, you go out of that first, that announcement, what were your guidelines that you personally adopted?
Oh, man.

never judge before i never judge never make a preconceived notion before you know everything were you determined to be non-prejudicial to the corps and the corps members um i was determined to be completely fair i was determined to be completely fair um in my opinion no one deserved more than someone else until they proved to me that they deserved more than anyone else
Until someone shows me that they're capable of more, I'm not going to give them more.
And were you determined that in doing anything with the Corps that you were not going to say, okay, buddies, I'll show you guys?
Oh, of course not.
No, I think that's one of the reasons why I might have gotten it.
It's because that was never an issue.
I did my job as my job was prescribed to me, not how I thought the job should be run.
All right, so then last summer, what?
Last summer was first jail.
I mean, I ate and braved that thing simply because Bill Cosby was the entertainer.
That's a whole lot of money Bill Cosby cost.
And so that was amazing, just having to put that together.
And throughout that time, my girlfriend and I had broken up.
And so personally, that was a really rough time just because we were going through all that.

Instead of breaking up with my girlfriend and really kind of re-evaluating who I was, re-evaluating my relationship with Christ, re-evaluating all that, I kind of went the other way and started having fun, per se, which I kind of regret now.
But it was good to do it, I guess, just because I learned a lot.
Was part of the problem of the breakup the stress of the activities, you reckon?
Sort of, possibly.
Because it was right before campaigning started.
And I was just, the whole stress of everything, I just started to wonder if I wanted to even do it anymore.

everything was like that like do I want to be a theater arts major like I started questioning everything so it was just kind of this I need to find myself I need to find who I am so you were you here all summer I was here all summer where'd you live I lived in a house over off 2818 and then when the fall semester began you moved to the campus yes back to Hart Hall Hart Hall
I lived in Hart Hall in the fall.
What was it like to live in Hart Hall?
It was great, man.
It was so neat just because I always got the weird look.
I always got the strange look.
I always got the what you live where.
I'm really into the strange looks that I get from people.
Like, I'm a theater arts major, so I'm liberal arts, so I need to take a language.
I'm taking ancient Greek as my language.
Exactly.
I love that look.
I love the look of people going...
I don't know necessarily why I do, but I just...
I don't know.
It's not that I love being different, per se, because I don't try to be different, but I loved living in Hart, and I love the stuff that I got living in Hart.
I love getting made fun of it.
Because it's on air-conditioned.
Because it's on air-conditioned, because my rooms weren't this big.
Everybody opens their window, so the wind was... You do know that long years ago, that was the athletic dorm.
Oh, yeah.
I remember.
I sure do.
Then classes began and first yell.
Classes began, first yell.
Did you get to meet Bill Cosby?
I did.
Actually, I got to meet Bill Cosby.
What was your impression?
Describe Bill.
Bill Cosby is the ultimate entertainer.
He is the entertainer.
It's amazing.
Sitting in the room, like when I was in there and Rusty Thompson, our advisor, would be in there and he'd be signing stuff for us.
He'd just kind of be there.
I mean, he'd be talking a little bit, but he would be talking very much like you and I are talking right now.
Not a big deal.
But then someone would come in, like he's real big into helping mentally challenged people and stuff like that.
Real, like he's really heavily involved in that.
And so some of the, some, there was a girl who loves Bill Cosby who is mentally challenged here in the Bryant College Station area.
And she came into the room.
And right when she came into the room, I mean the switch went on.
And he was Dr. Huxtable.
I mean he was Bill Cosby that you hear on radio, that you see on TV.
And she left, and he was just, I mean, just sat down.
He was just very tired looking.
I mean, the man's 70 years old.
And he did not, in his presentation, did not do or even hint at a thing that was inappropriate.
Never was.
That was in bad taste or anything.
That's what I thought.
Never was.
And that's another thing, is right beforehand, he was so tired.
But then he hit the, I mean, it was just, oh, man, just on.
I mean, right when he walked out that curtain, it was on.
Then right when he got off stage...
Was he courteous to everyone?
Very courteous.
Oh, he took every picture that anyone wanted to take.
He signed everything that anyone wanted to sign.
All that stuff.
It was great.
So, all right, as head yell leader, what were some of the high points and low points, if there were any for you?
Some of the high points were just getting to be involved with what I got to be involved in.
Something that I've learned throughout my time as head yell leader is that I love to be on the in.
Does that make sense?
To be what?
And on the in, be the one that someone calls if they need something.
On the in, I-N.
Yeah, be on the in, I guess you could say.
Being on a first name basis with Dr. Sutherland.
You know, the fact that every time I see him, he makes fun of me.
You know, that type of stuff.
I enjoy that.
I do.
And so that was a really neat thing.
High point for just as far as Yale leader goes, seeing First Yale happen.
and that getting done, and realizing that it was a success, not only that it worked, but also financially, we made a lot of money.
As far as you know, it's continuing.
And it's continuing.

And I think that that's, and it's really, it's a really neat thing to know that we were in on the beginning of that, those five of us, that sat in that room and said, okay, if we're going to do this, then we need to do it.
And then seeing it happen.
Any low moments?
Disappointments?
Times, yeah.
I mean, just problems with friendships again.
I mean, I was even busier this semester, this past fall, than I was this semester before.
So a lot of friendships were fading.
There was times in which I didn't like my living situation.
The guy I was living with was a sophomore.
I was having problems with other friends.
I wasn't with my girlfriend, obviously.
I got myself into some situations with girls that were bad.
Not anything serious or anything, but just...
If I had it all over again, I wouldn't do it simply because of just the emotion that had to be put forth to appease the situation.
So that wasn't good.
Now, through all of these stressful times, sometimes stressful times, to whom did you turn for advice, for counseling?
Different people, honestly.
The person that first came to my mind was my girlfriend, Kate.
Even when we weren't together, if I was having a bad time, I'd call her.
And she'd always listen.
Another one is Dr. Welch, Ben Welch, who was the advisor to the Aggie Men's Club.
We eat breakfast every Thursday morning at 7 o'clock in the morning.
He and whoever else wants to come, but it's usually just me and him.
And that is, that's just, he's just an amazing sounding board.
What about academic advice?
What to take or what not to take?
Just my fellow students, my fellow theater art students, really.
Now, you and your friends register on the machine.
It's on the phone.
On the phone, okay.
And how long does that take?
Oh my gosh, my freshman year it took until about 2.15 in the morning.
Now it doesn't take that long just because I'm older.
You know the routine.
I know the routine a little better.
How do you avoid taking the wrong course?
Gas, man.
Like really what it is is you sign up for stuff and then you realize what you're in and then you go talk to an advisor.
I talk to my advisors a lot, see what courses I need, see what I don't.
Do you have a long-range career goal yet?
I've got a pretty good idea of some.
What is it?
I would like...
I don't know, to be honest with you.
I know that I like the arts.
I enjoy acting.
I love being on stage.
I love that type of stuff.
I love building sets, and I love that.
But then I also love...
I got to go to the inauguration this year for George W. I love that.
I love politics.
I love...
I love having a cause and defending it.
I'm not saying that politics is something that I'm going to be in, but it very well could be.
Politics is something that I'm in.
And your major today is?
Theater arts.
Theater arts.
And I have a minor in business.
And you're graduating when?
Next May.
And... What am I going to do?
What are you going to do?
Oh, gosh.
I have no idea.
My parents have a lot of contacts in Washington right now simply because of who's there.
I could go get a job in Washington.
They've already told me that, that I could go get work in Washington for a while, maybe even in the White House.
I agree.
Stuff I thought about.
As you look at this campus today, how are the co-eds treated?
Very well, I think.
Are they, you think, given equality?
I believe so.
I believe so.
If you go over to student government and if you go to the MSC and if you go to stuff like that, women are doing just as much as men are and sometimes even more.
If you look at Fish Camp, the organization of Fish Camp, there are always, always a majority of people that help out women.
and that's very, that's looked well upon.

If you look at administrators, yes, top administrators are still males, simply because of, and this is nothing against y'all, simply because of the age in which the males are, simply because the administrators are now 50s, 60s.
Most women who are in 50 and 60 didn't get the education to support that.
But I say in the next 20 years, a majority of the, I wouldn't say majority, but I'd say a very equal part of the administrators on this campus will be women.
I mean, just like Dr. Winterford,
Cindy Lawson, people like that.
There are people in key positions on campus that make big time decisions.
And so I think that it's coming around.
Probably slower here than other places, but I think it's coming around.
What about minorities?
Minorities, it's a funny thing.
Minorities aren't, it's different here than other places.
I think it's open to them, but the minority has to be very open as well.
Does that make sense?
The minority person can't come in here with a chip on the shoulder because a chip is just going to be given right back to them.
But someone who is open, like Boo-Boo, like a Ronnie McDonald, like my friend Sko Maps, he's African-American.
If they're open, then there's nothing that's going to be done.
What about Asian?
Asian, I have another friend who was just an exec on a...
And a student organization, big MSC hospitality, very big student organization, he could probably do anything he wanted in student government.
I think that it's relatively open.
But I think a big part of it is, and this stinks, but it's on their part.
And what they are, are they going to subscribe to the same things that we hold dear?
Because if they try and come and change the system, then obviously we aren't, we wouldn't have that even if a, I mean if a Caucasian came in and did that.
make believe that I didn't know anything about the student body in general here.
Geographically, where do Aggie undergraduates come from?
Texas.
Big towns, small towns?
I think it's half and half.
Now, honestly, a lot of people come from the cities.
A lot of people come from Houston, Austin, Dallas.
A lot of people.
Are there still small towners?
They're very small towners.

in terms of attitudes a liberal conservative conservative very conservative but it's getting more liberal it's funny um i would say more liberal conservatism if that's if that's said um just because a lot of people they aren't die hard right-wing conservatives yet at the same time they aren't i think that's i think that's the biggest thing is that they're actually
In my opinion, we have a much more open-minded campus than people would like to think.
Maybe I'm just optimistic.
As you have now finished four years, who are the people in key positions here that you most respect?
I'm not going to ask the negative.
That I most respect?
I respect Cindy Lawson.
Now, how do you know her?
Through the bonfire stuff, and then just in the position that I've held these past couple years.
I respect Winn Rosser, who works in the vice president's office for student affairs.
What's his task?
His task is pretty much to go wherever Dr. Sutherland goes and follow him around.
But the thing about Dr. Rosser is that he never misses anything.
He's kind of a chief of staff.
Yeah.
He doesn't miss a thing.
Does not miss a thing.
And it's really neat to see that.
I respect Rusty Thompson, who is our advisor.
Rusty has probably been much more than just an advisor.
I mean, Rusty and I are gonna be close.
Maybe it's just simply because of the stuff that we had to go through.
But Rusty and I will be close probably for the rest of his life, at least I'd like to think so.
I mean, there's more, but those are the ones that stick out.
Mm-hm, mm-hm.
If you were giving advice to the Head Yale leaders of the future, what advice would you give them?
of yourself because you were put in the position by your friends.
There's nothing that you did necessarily that put you in the position.
There's everything that everyone else did.
Be humble just because you don't deserve it necessarily.
You were put there for a purpose.
Be open-minded at all times.
Don't think that just because that's how it was done in the past means that that's the right way to do it.
before you make a decision, remove yourself from the situation, then think about what would be best for the student body as a whole, not just for the organization.
If you had complete authority to make any changes in what we do in terms of athletic events and so forth, is there anything you would change?
Any yells you would discontinue?
Any songs you would modify or terminate?
I can't think of any.
I'm very happy with how stuff goes right now.
If I could change anything, it'd be that we have a better basketball team.
I mean, I would change certain things about the athletic teams themselves, but nothing.
Nothing about the way in which we, as Aggies, support our teams.
See, if I had dictator authority, and my notes don't go in the final version, of course, if I were the dictator, we would sing the other verse of the war hymn.
That's a really funny thing that comes up.
That's a funny talk because, I don't know, we get asked that a lot, about why don't we sing the first verse.
And it's actually not the first verse.
It's actually the second verse.
Yeah, yeah.
Yes, I mean, I don't think that would be a horrible thing to do.
See, like when I was chancellor at Missouri and NM came up there and played, and this would have been 89 or 90.
And here, playing at Missouri, you don't beat the hell out of...
and goodbye to Texas University and the Missouri Crown was saying, gee, you know, these people are superb, but why are they singing that here?
Well, it's just, I mean, what I tell people is we aren't seeing that thinking of Texas necessarily.
I know it, yeah.
You don't think of Texas necessarily.
Maybe the first verse, I think that's something that might come up later.
I remember a couple years ago a big push was done for that and it just didn't catch.
I remember stories of them even passing out the words at Yale practice and people crumpling it up and throwing it back on the field.
One thing that I've learned is that if the student body doesn't want it, then you're not going to do it.
You're not going to do it.
That's true.
That's true.
Let's see.
Since you were in the Corps, you'd seen your boots.
I wasn't in the Corps.
Yeah, and you don't yet have a senior ring.
I get that.
I order this after the semester.
How do you think you're going to feel when you put it on?
I'm gonna feel good.
I'm gonna feel real good.
It's gonna be like a job well done.
And is it a special thing you think?
Yeah.
I'm never gonna take it off.
What creates Aggie spirit?
Why is there the pride in this institution?
It's a hard question to put words on.
Are there some events that contribute to it?
Of course, there's always events.

I mean, with any culture that you have, there's going to be the rituals that you have that add to the culture, such as football games, such as yell practice, muster, silver taps, stuff like that, fish camp, yell leaders, reveille, stuff like that.
The Corps of Cadets, I think, is a big thing that adds to that.
The fact that we have something like that to do.
A willingness to be part of it is what really does.
Because anybody can come in here and you can shove the traditions down someone's throat, but if they don't want to be a part of them, then they're not going to mean anything.
But the great thing about A&M is you get all these people that are willing to do it.
Is A&M inclusive of people?
Mm-hmm.
if that person is willing, if that person is willing, if that person is willing to come in and be like, I'm not going to feel stupid when I do this.
I will do this because the people before me did it.
See, I believe that many outsiders think A&M is not inclusive.
Yeah.
I believe it's very inclusive.
I believe it's very inclusive.
In the interviews I've done with people back in the 30s and 40s, it didn't matter where you came from, what your daddy did.
If you were a part of the group,
And if you would join and do your part, well done.
Like y'all don't give people nicknames.
Everybody then had a nickname.
And the nickname to an outsider seemed like a put down.
But it wasn't.
It was an identifier.
Faculty all had nicknames.
Like you've never heard of Cube Root Jackson or Square Root Jackson or Cube Root Kent.
they taught two very, very key math courses that all engineers had to take.
And the myth was that the courses were so hard that only the square root of the number of students taking the course would pass it.
I can imagine.
Then there was another guy, Dr. Dan, the grade point man, Dan Russell, over in rural sociology.
And if you needed some grade points, you took one.
You'd go there.
And you knew it, and he knew it.
He knew why you were there.
So you think it is inclusive.
Let's see, you've not been through a commencement yet, so that question doesn't...
doesn't fit.
At this point, what are you most proud about being a part of A&M?
The fact that people are willing to do so much for this institution with no thank yous.
I think the fact that we've got students and faculty that do stuff for A&M and not even all of them are Aggies.
I mean, some of them aren't even Aggies.
We have a very giving, giving culture.
Are there some faculty members that have touched you?
Some.
Importantly?
Some.
Who?
Arnold Kramer is one of them.
Okay.
Ben Welch is another.
Rusty Thompson is one.
Patricia Weiner is another one.
W-E-H-N-E-R?
Like the building.
And what does she do?
She is administrative helper for the Yalmeters Memorial Student Center.
And the grades that you've earned here, do you think that in general you got what you deserve?
Mm-hmm.
Sometimes.
Other times, I didn't have to go to class and I could get the A, so.
That's right.
Sometimes.
I mean, it's just, it's very dependent on the class.
I mean, there, there are obviously those teachers that are just like being the grade point man.
There's, there are, there are still those here.
If you were a consultant to A&M's leaders today, we brought you in to advise.
What advice would you give them about how to guide A&M toward even greater
Don't be hostile to the critic.
I guess.
Don't be hostile to the critic.
Any other?
Say thank you.
Okay.
Individual thank yous.
Don't forget to do that.
See, Jack Williams was superb.
You got a personal note, handwritten.
It only had three lines to it, but it was to you.
That's great.
Oh, of course you did.
Of course you did.
What about A&M's size?
I want it bigger.
Bigger?
Mm-hmm.
Can it remain personal?
Mm-hmm.
How would you select the students to be admitted?
That's tough.
I don't like the 10% rule.
I don't like it.
All right, what would you have as your guidelines?
A lot of the same stuff that we have now, except it wouldn't be automatic for someone who's in the top 10%.
Would you give?
All right, I'm reading in.
class rank plus ACTSAT.
Sure.
Class rank with a combination of grades but a combination of other stuff too.
I think the great things that make A&M is that we don't just get students.
We don't just get academics.
We get people that are involved in other stuff.
That's what makes A&M strong because someone can come through with their 2.7 which is a very
Even grade point average, I mean, that's the average, but do amazing things on this campus.
There are people that come through with 4.0 that never do anything except take grades, which is good.
You need both.
And so that's why I think I would just do away with the 10 percent rule.
In my opinion, that would mean a lot more work for the admissions people.
Well, and see, that's a state law, so.
Oh, I know.
But maybe it's going to be modified this year.
All right, I've got only two other questions.
What have we not talked about that we should have included?
What have you thought of that, if anything?
